## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It was removed because it corrupts application state by injecting exceptions at arbitrary points.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is also removed** — no equivalent needed.
3. The idiomatic replacement is **`CancellationToken` + `Task.Run`**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result;

            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is not null)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            ExceptionDispatchInfo.Capture(ex.InnerException).Throw();
            throw; // unreachable, satisfies compiler
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work supports cancellation (preferred)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Fire-and-forget work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work()` ignores the token, it keeps running in the background after timeout. |
| **`Task.Result` deadlock** | Never call `.Result` on a UI/sync-context thread. Use the async version above when possible. |
| **Resource leaks** | The abandoned work may hold DB connections, file handles, etc. Ensure `work` respects cancellation or wraps resources in `using`. |
| **Exception shape change** | Original threw `AggregateException(inner)`. The migrated sync version preserves the inner exception directly via `ExceptionDispatchInfo`. Callers catching `AggregateException` must be updated. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` references** | Search your codebase for any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` — replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |

### Migration Checklist

1. Replace all `Thread.Abort()` / `ResetAbort()` calls — they throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`
2. Refactor long-running work to accept `CancellationToken` and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points
3. Update callers to handle `OperationCanceledException` instead of `ThreadAbortException`
4. Prefer the `async` variant — the sync version blocks a thread pool thread
